# Intuition
We can use binary search to find out which element is exactly greater than or equal to product of ```spells[i]``` and ```potions[i]```.
1) we just need to take care of long variable as product maybe go beyond int range.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
1) Sort potions array ascending order. So that we can use binary search to find out minimum element that is less than success.
2) now we need to check for every element in spells, so let's use a for loop and pass our binary Search.
```
for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
    arr[i] = bs(potions, spells[i], success, 0, m - 1);
}
```
3) In binary search if we found ```spells[i] * potions[mid] >= success``` it means there maybe other element in the left side that are maybe greater than or equal to success. So, we use ```end = mid - 1``` else ```start = mid + 1```.
4) Now for count all the numbers we just need to subtract ```potion.length - start```.
5) We can easily store these count in spells array as we don't need previous values further. So we don't need any extra space
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
- $$O(n logn)$$
