# 2nd way 

<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
##### •	The problem requires us to find the number of successful pairs between spells and potions, where a pair is considered successful if the product of the spell and potion is greater than or equal to a given value called success.
##### •	We can start by sorting the potions array in increasing order, as this will help us in finding the minimum potion required for a given spell.
##### •	For each spell, we need to find the minimum value of potion whose product with the current spell will be at least success or more. We can calculate this value by dividing success by the spell and taking the ceiling of the result.
##### •	If the minimum potion required is greater than the maximum potion available, then we cannot form any successful pairs for this spell. In this case, we can set the answer for this spell to 0 and move on to the next spell.
##### •	If we have a potion that can be used with the current spell, we need to find the index of the first potion in the sorted array that is greater than or equal to the minimum potion required. We can use binary search to find this index.
##### •	Once we have the index of the first potion that can be used, we can count the number of potions to the right of this index, as all these potions will be greater than or equal to the minimum potion required and can be used to form successful pairs with the current spell.
##### •	We repeat steps 3 to 6 for all spells and return the answer array containing the number of successful pairs for each spell.

